Ingingo ya 60: Abanditsi b’irangamimerere 

(1) Abanditsi b’irangamimerere ni aba bakurikira: 
(a) umukozi ufite irangamimerere mu nshingano ku rwego rw’imitegekere y’Igihugu rwegerejwe abaturage; 
(b) Ambasaderi w’u Rwanda mu mahanga; 
(c) umukozi wo mu kigo cy’ubuvuzi. 
(2) Iteka rya Minisitiri ufite 
irangamimerere mu nshingano rishobora kugena undi muntu ufite inshingano z’umwanditsi w’irangamimerere. 

Article 60: Civil registrars 

(1) Civil registrars are the following: 
(a) a civil registrar at the level of a decentralized administrative entity; 
(b) a head of a diplomatic mission of Rwanda abroad; 
(c) an officer of a health facility. 
(2) An Order of the Minister in charge of civil status may determine another person performing the duties of a civil registrar

Article 67: Types of civil status registers 
Ingingo ya 67: Ubwoko bw’ibitabo by’irangamimerere 

(1) Civil status registers are the following: 
(1) Ibitabo by’irangamimerere ni ibi bikurikira: 
(a) igitabo cy’inyandiko z’amavuko; 
(a) register of birth records; 
(b) igitabo cy’inyandiko z’abapfuye; 
(b) register of death records; 
(c) igitabo cy’inyandiko z’abashyingiranywe 
(c) register of marriage records; 
(d) igitabo cy’inyandiko z’ubwishingire; 
(d) register of guardianship records; 
(e) igitabo cy’inyandiko zerekeye kwemera abana bavutse ku batarashyingiranywe; 
(e) register of records of recognition of children born out of wedlock; 
(f) igitabo cy’inyandiko zerekeye kwemera kubera umubyeyi umwana utabyaye; 
(f) register of adoption records; 
(g) igitabo cy’inyandiko zerekeye ubutane; 
(g) register of divorce records;

Article 111: Grounds for establishing the guardianship of child 
Ingingo ya 111: Impamvu zituma habaho ubwishingire bw’umwana Ubwishingire bw’umwana bubaho iyo – 
The guardianship of a child is established due to the following grounds – 
(a) in case of death, disappearance, absence of both parents or when they are unknown; 
(a) se na nyina bapfuye, bazimiye, babuze cyangwa batazwi; 
(b) abo yitaga se na nyina bamwihakanye; 
(b) in case of denial of paternity or maternity; 
(c) ababyeyi bakiriho ariko barambuwe ububasha bwa kibyeyi; 
(c) when both parents are still alive but deprived of parental authority; or 
(d) cyangwa umubyeyi usigaye afite ubumuga bumubuza kurangiza inshingano za kibyeyi. 
(d) when the surviving parent has a disability preventing him or her from fulfilling his or her parental responsibility. 


Article 154: Family council and its purpose 
Ingingo ya 154: Inama y’umuryango n’intego yayo 
(1) Inama y’umuryango ni urwego rwo mu muryango rushinzwe guteza imbere umuryango, kurengera inyungu z’abawugize no gukemura ibibazo biwuvutsemo. 
(1) The family council is an organ within the family responsible for development of the family, safeguarding interests of the family members and settling the disputes arising in the family. 
(2) An Order of the Minister in charge of family determines the members of the family council, its duties, organisation and functioning. 
(2) Iteka rya Minisitiri ufite umuryango mu nshingano rigena abagize inama y’umuryango, inshingano, imiterere n’imikorere byayo. 

Article 155: Community of property regime and management of property 
Ingingo ya 155: Ivangamutungo rusange n’imicungire y’umutungo 
(1) Ivangamutungo rusange ni uburyo abashyingiranywe bumvikana bwo gushyira hamwe umutungo wabo wose. 
(1) The community of property regime is a method by which the spouses opt for joint ownership of all their property. 
(2) Gucunga umutungo bijyana n’ububasha bwo kuwucunga, kuwikenuza no kuwikuraho. 
(2) The management of property comprises of powers of administration, enjoyment and disposal. 
(3) Abashyingiranywe bahisemo ivangamutungo rusange bacungira hamwe umutungo wabo kandi bakagira ububasha bungana bwo kuwukurikirana no kuwuhagararira. 
(3) Spouses under the community of property regime jointly manage their property and have the same power of monitoring and representation over the property. 
(4) A property registered in the name of one of the spouses is part of the property belonging to spouses under the community of property regime. The property cannot be sold, given in liberality or be disposed without both spouses’ agreement. 
(4) Umutungo wanditse kuri umwe mu bashyingiranywe ubarirwa mu mutungo wabo mu buryo bw’ivangamutungo rusange. Umutungo ntushobora kugurishwa, gutangwa cyangwa kuwikuraho abashyingiranywe bombi batabyemeranyijweho. 
(5) Abashyingiranywe bafatanya kwishyura imyenda yafashwe mbere yo gushyingirwa n’iyo bemeranyije gufata nyuma yo gushyingirwa. Bafatanya kandi kubahiriza inshingano umwe yafashe mbere y’ishyingirwa. 
(5) Spouses are jointly liable for debts incurred before their marriage and other debts they have agreed to take after their marriage. They are jointly bound by the obligations that one of the spouses engaged in before marriage. 


Ingingo ya 157: Ivangamutungo w’umuhahano n’uburyo rikorwa 
Ivangamutungo w’umuhahano ni uburyo abashyingiranywe bumvikana bwo gushyira hamwe umutungo bazahaha bari kumwe kuva ku munsi w’ishyingirwa, kimwe n’ibyo bungutse mu mibanire yabo, bakorera hamwe cyangwa buri wese ku giti cye, byaba impano cyangwa ibizungurwa. 
Article 157: Limited community of property regime and its conclusion 
Limited community of property regime is a method by which spouses agree to pool their respective properties owned from the date of marriage, as well as the property acquired during marriage by a common or separate activity, either donation or succession. 

Ingingo ya 162: Ivanguramutungo risesuye n’uburyo rikorwa 
Ivanguramutungo risesuye ni uburyo abashyingiranywe bumvikana gufatanya gutunga urugo rwabo hakurikijwe ubushobozi bwa buri wese, kandi buri wese akagumana ububasha bwo gucunga, kwikenuza no kwikuraho umutungo we bwite. 

Article 162: Separation of property regime and its conclusion 
Separation of property regime is a method by which spouses agree to contribute to the expenses of the household in proportion to their respective abilities while each spouse retains the power of administration, enjoyment and disposal of his or her personal property. 

Ingingo ya 166: Imicungire y’umutungo 
w’abashyingiranywe ishingiye ku masezerano ategurwa n’abashaka gushyingiranwa Abagiye gushyingiranwa bashobora guhitamo uburyo bw’imicungire y’umutungo bushingiye ku masezerano ategurwa na bo ubwabo iyo itanyuranyije n’amategeko ndemyagihugu n’imyifatire mbonezabupfura y’Abanyarwanda. 
Article 166: Matrimonial regime based on agreement drawn up by intending spouses 
Intending spouses may choose matrimonial regime based on agreement drawn up by them if it is not contrary to the rules of public order and good 
morals of Rwandans. 


Article 173: Reasons for dissolution of matrimonial regime 
Ingingo ya 173: Impamvu z’iseswa ry’uburyo bw’imicungire y’umutungo w’abashyingiranywe 
The type of matrimonial regime is dissolved for one of the following reasons: 
Uburyo bw’imicungire y’umutungo w’abashyingiranywe buseswa kubera imwe mu mpamvu zikurikira: 

(a) divorce; 
(a) ubutane; 
(b) change of type of matrimonial regime; 
(b) guhindura uburyo bw’imicungire y’umutungo w’abashyingiranywe; 
(c) death of one of the spouses. 
(c) urupfu rw’umwe mu bashyingiranywe. 


Article 248: Grounds for divorce 
Ingingo ya 248: Impamvu z’ubutane 
(1) Buri wese mu bashyingiranywe ashobora gusaba ubutane kubera imwe mu mpamvu zikurikira: 
(1) Each of the spouses may lodge a claim for divorce on one of the following grounds: 
(a) adultery; 
(a) ubusambanyi; 
(b) desertion of matrimonial home by one of the spouses without justifiable ground for at least 12 consecutive months; 
(b) kuba umwe mu bashyingiranywe yarataye urugo nta mpamvu ifite ishingiro nibura mu gihe cy’amezi 12 akurikirana; 
(c) a conviction for an offense severely damaging reputation; 
(c) guhamwa n’icyaha gisebeje; 
(d) kwanga gutanga ibitunga urugo; 
(d) refusal to provide for household expenses; 
(e) ihohoterwa ku mubiri, ku mitekerereze, ihohoterwa rishengura umutima, irishingiye ku mutungo cyangwa imyitwarire ibangamiye bikabije urega, umwana bahuriyeho bombi, umwana w’urega cyangwa w’uregwa; 
(e) physical, psychological, emotional violence, economic harm or grossly abusive conduct against the claimant, a common child, a child of the claimant or of the defendant; 
(f) gender based violence; 
(f) ihohoterwa rishingiye ku gitsina; 
(g) de facto separation for a period of at least two years; 
(g) kumara nibura imyaka ibiri batabana ku bushake bwabo; 
(h) kutabana mu gihe kirenze amezi atandatu akurikirana uhereye igihe habereye ishyingirwa nta mpamvu zifite ishingiro zihari; 
(h) non-cohabitation for more than six consecutive months from the date of celebration of marriage without valid grounds; 
(i) if the cohabitation becomes impossible due to irreconcilable differences of one of the spouses. 
(i) iyo kubana bitagishobotse kubera indi mpamvu itakwihanganirwa n’umwe mu bashyingiranywe. 

(2) Kutabana bitewe n’uko umwe mu bashyingiranywe afashwe nabi ntibyitwa guta urugo mu gihe yagiye abimenyesheje ubuyobozi bw’ibanze bumwegereye bigakorerwa inyandiko. 
(2) The non-cohabitation following mistreatment of one of the spouses cannot be considered as desertion of matrimonial home if the victim spouse has informed the nearest local administration before leaving the matrimonial home and a record thereto has been drawn. 

Ingingo 198: Imiziro mu gushyingirwa 
Article 198: Prohibited marriage 


(1) Gushyingiranwa hagati y’abantu bafitanye isano ikurikira kurabujijwe: 
(1) Marriage between persons with the following relationships is prohibited: 

(a) direct lineal kinship; 
(a) isano y’ubuvandimwe itaziguye; 
(b) collateral kinship up to the seventh degree; 
(b) isano y’ubuvandimwe iziguye kugeza ku gisanira cya karindwi; 
(c) a person and his or her parents-in-law; 
(c) sebukwe cyangwa nyirabukwe w’umuntu; 
(d) the adoptive parent and the adoptee; 
(d) uwemeye kubera umubyeyi umwana atabyaye n’uwo mwana; 
(e) the adoptive parent and the descendants of the adoptee; 
(e) uwemeye kubera umubyeyi umwana atabyaye n’abakomoka kuri uwo mwana; 
(f) the adoptee and the spouse of the adoptive parent; 
(f) uwagizwe umwana n’utaramubyaye n’uwashyingiranywe n’uwamugize umwana; 
(g) the adoptive parent and the spouse of the adopted person; 
(g) uwemeye kubera umubyeyi umwana atabyaye n’uwashyingiranywe n’uwo mwana; 
(h) abagizwe abana n’umuntu umwe utarababyaye; 
(h) the adopted persons from a same adoptive parent; 
(i) the adopted person and the children of the adoptive parent. 
(i) uwagizwe umwana n’utaramubyaye n’abana b’uwo mubyeyi we. 
(2) Prohibitions provided for in Subparagraphs (h) and (i) of this Article may be lifted for serious reasons upon authorisation by the civil registrar at District level. 
(2) Imiziro iteganyijwe mu duka twa (h) na (i) tw’iyi ngingo ishobora kutitabwaho umwanditsi w’irangamimerere wo ku rwego rw’Akarere abitangiye uruhushya kubera impamvu zikomeye.
